nsion of NATO to include former communist allies of Russia as well as three of its former republics, the American decision to invade Iraq in 2003, and the Russian move to invade Georgia in 2008. This book uses a number of key theories in political science to create a framework for analysis and to outline policy options for the future. It is vital that the attentive public confront the questions raised in these pages in order to control the reflexive and knee-jerk reactions to all points of conflict that emerge on a regular basis between America and Russia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aInternational Relations 2020. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aCrimea.  aNATO.  ainvasions.  arelationship.  aterrorism.1 aPeterson, James W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615709640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526157096423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526157096/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles